- Context: This is the second page of the Risk Assessment Methodologies PDF, detailing the scope, qualitative and quantitative risk assessment principles.
- Text: 4. Introduction
This document focuses on the application of qualitative and quantitative risk assessment
methodologies in industrial environments. The application of risk assessment is central to
the identification of potential hazards and the assessment of the potential consequences
and likelihoods. Qualitative and quantitative risk assessments are important risk
assessment techniques which are used to support the identification of hazards and risks
and provide a mechanism to determine the level of risk. This will then allow for
appropriate mitigation measures to be implemented to minimise or eliminate risk.
5. Qualitative Risk Assessment
5.1 Principles of Qualitative Risk Assessment
Qualitative risk assessment is the process of subjectively determining the probability of
occurrence and the severity of the consequences of a potential event to determine its risk
level. It is an effective way to identify and evaluate risks that are difficult to measure
quantitatively. Qualitative risk assessment can be used as a standalone assessment
technique, or it can be used in conjunction with quantitative risk assessment.
Qualitative risk assessment relies heavily on the knowledge and experience of the
assessment team to identify hazards and assess risks.
Qualitative risk assessment should consider a range of factors, including:
0
The nature of the activity or process being assessed
•
0
The potential hazards associated with the activity or process
The potential consequences of the hazards
The likelihood of the consequences occurring
The existing control measures in place
The effectiveness of the existing control measures
The vulnerability of the system or process to the hazards
The potential impact of the hazards on people, the environment, and assets
6. Quantitative Risk Assessment
6.1 Principles of Quantitative Risk Assessment
Quantitative risk assessment is the process of objectively determining the probability of
occurrence and the severity of the consequences of a potential event to determine its risk
level. It uses numerical data and statistical analysis to estimate the probability and
severity of the consequences.
